   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-pred-md",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Simple Prediction — Mental Health Status Classifier"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-encode",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Encode boolean keyword columns as integers\n",
    "for col in bool_cols:\n",
    "    df_clean[col + '_int'] = df_clean[col].astype(int)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Encode target label\n",
    "le = LabelEncoder()\n",
    "df_clean['status_encoded'] = le.fit_transform(df_clean['status'])\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Label encoding:')\n",
    "for i, cls in enumerate(le.classes_):\n",
    "    print(f'  {i} → {cls}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-encode-explain",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The boolean keyword columns are converted to `0/1` integers so they can be used as numeric features. The `status` column (our target) is label-encoded: each of the four mental health categories is mapped to a unique integer (0–3)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-split",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "feature_cols = [\n",
    "    'text_length', 'word_count', 'avg_word_length', 'stopword_ratio',\n",
    "    'type_token_ratio', 'polarity', 'subjectivity',\n",
    "    'noun_ratio', 'verb_ratio', 'adj_ratio', 'adv_ratio',\n",
    "    'has_suicidal_keyword_int', 'has_stress_keyword_int', 'has_help_keyword_int'\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "X = df_clean[feature_cols]\n",
    "y = df_clean['status_encoded']\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42, stratify=y\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Training set size:  {X_train.shape[0]:,} rows')\n",
    "print(f'Test set size:      {X_test.shape[0]:,} rows')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-split-explain",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We use 14 numeric/binary features as inputs. The data is split 80% train / 20% test with `stratify=y` to ensure each mental health category is proportionally represented in both sets."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-model",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)\n",
    "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "y_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n",
    "acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'\\n✅ Test Accuracy: {acc:.4f} ({acc*100:.2f}%)')\n",
    "print('\\nClassification Report:')\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=le.classes_))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cell-model-explain",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**What the result means:** The Random Forest model correctly predicts the mental health category from text features with reasonable accuracy. In plain terms — given how someone writes (how long their post is, how negative it sounds, what kind of words they use), the model can make an educated guess about whether they are expressing Anxiety, Depression, Normal mood, or Suicidal thoughts. Because the features are purely stylistic and do not include the actual words, the accuracy is limited but still meaningful — it shows that *how* people write differs across mental health states."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cell-feature-importance",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
